Answer: Here is a basic Maven `pom.xml` template for a Java project:

```xml
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
  xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <!-- Project Information -->
  <groupId>com.example</groupId>
  <artifactId>myproject</artifactId>
  <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
  <packaging>jar</packaging>

  <!-- Project Name and Description -->
  <name>My Project</name>
  <description>This is my project.</description>

  <!-- Project Properties -->
  <properties>
    <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>
    <maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source>
    <maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target>
  </properties>

  <!-- Project Dependencies -->
  <dependencies>
    <!-- Add your dependencies here -->
  </dependencies>

  <!-- Project Build Settings -->
  <build>
    <plugins>
      <plugin>
        <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
        <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
        <version>3.8.1</version>
        <configuration>
          <source>${maven.compiler.source}</source>
          <target>${maven.compiler.target}</target>
        </configuration>
      </plugin>
    </plugins>
  </build>
</project>
```

**Method 1: Using `zellij` command**

1. Press `Ctrl + A` to enter command mode.
2. Type `:copy` and press Enter.
3. The entire scrollback buffer will be copied to the system clipboard.

**Method 2: Using `zellij` command with a range**

1. Press `Ctrl + A` to enter command mode.
2. Type `:copy <start_line> <end_line>` and press Enter.
Replace `<start_line>` and `<end_line>` with the line numbers you want to copy. For example, `:copy 10 20` will copy lines 10 to 20.

**Method 3: Using `zellij` command with a selection**

1. Press `Ctrl + A` to enter command mode.
2. Type `:copy` and press Enter.
3. Use your mouse or keyboard to select the text you want to copy.
4. Press `Ctrl + C` to copy the selected text to the system clipboard.

**Method 4: Using an external tool**

You can also use an external tool like `xclip` or `pbcopy` to copy the scrollback buffer to the system clipboard.

1. Install `xclip` or `pbcopy` on your system.
2. Press `Ctrl + A` to enter command mode.
3. Type `:exec xclip -selection clipboard` (or `pbcopy` on macOS) and press Enter.
4. The entire scrollback buffer will be copied to the system clipboard.
